Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) are considered multipotent based on their ability to differentiate into osteoblasts, chondroblasts, and adipocytes—key markers defined by international standards—and further supported by direct references stating they can generate cells from bone, cartilage, muscle, and fat lineages. These findings align with established definitions confirming their limited but distinct multilineage differentiation capability.  

\boxed{A} The provided information supports that MSCs exhibit multipotency through documented differentiation into specific connective tissue-derived cell types under standardized conditions. 

